Hay Festival 2013: John Guy and 16th-century gossip
Tudor historian John Guy reveals the bedroom gossip from the reign of one of England's most influential monarchs, Henry VIII, at Hay Festival.
Historian John Guy on site at the Hay Festival 2013 Photo: Martin Chilton	By Martin Chilton, Culture Editor Online
1:56PM BST 30 May 2013
Follow Comments
John Guy has a gift for bringing Tudor times to life and those at his talk on his new book, The Children of Henry VIII, were treated to some serious history and 16th-century gossip.
Catherine Parr, queen of England and the last of Henry's six wives, "knew how to torture Henry," Guy said, adding: "She was the Tudor Imelda Marcos, amassing 250 pairs of smart shoes within two years...Jimmy Choo had nothing on her."
Henry VIII, England’s wealthiest and most powerful king who became the subject of the most notorious divorce case of the 16th century, and broke with the Pope, had his marriage to Anne of Cleeves annulled in 1540 on the grounds of non-consummation. She later revealed, said Guy, that "Henry was no good in bed". During a court trial, when Thomas Cromwell was trying to suppress the truth, a note was read out by Anne that said (again, using Guy's colourful shorthand description) that Henry "could not get it up". Henry claimed that this was an affliction only with her. If he had been deemed impotent, he would not have been allowed to marry again.
Guy said that recent American medical research suggests that Henry had a positive blood antigen that would have made it difficult for his children to survive. His first child died after only seven weeks in 1511 but he did father four living children, each by a different mother.
The sections of the talk about his children were engrossing. In 1519 he had Henry Fitzroy - by the glamorous mistress known as Bessie Blount - and Henry provided top tutors from Cambridge for the boy from the age of six. He wasn't fussed about girls and left Catherine of Aragon to teach his daughter to read. It wasn't exactly an age of feminist enlightenment. It was reasonable for a mistress to answer back to a king but not a wife.
