Guy talked about Henry's affairs (with Anne Boleyn and her sister) and said Henry rarely saw his children (there were only three occasions when all the surviving children were together) and Guy remarked of the son Edward that "he was Henry VIII without the subtlety." Guy was fascinating on the character similarities between the ruthless, vain and subtle Henry and his children.
There was a lot to roam across in an hour but the long queue for the book signing suggested visitors wanted to find out more about the dysfunctional Tudors. There was just time at the end for a snippet about Lady Jane Grey. The historian said that new information was casting new light on some of the "doctored documents" of the 16th century about her. Sounds like there is another book in it.
